In probability theory, conditional independence describes situations in which an observation is irrelevant or redundant when evaluating the certainty of a hypothesis. It is the opposite of conditional dependence. Conditional independence is usually formulated in terms of conditional probability, as a special case where the probability of the hypothesis given the uninformative observation is equal to the probability without. If 



A


{\displaystyle A}

